Good morning,

This week=E2=80=99s Stratechery Interview is with Byrne Hobart ( https://x.=
com/ByrneHobart ). Hobart writes The Diff ( https://www.thediff.co/ ) , a n=
ewsletter about technological change as expressed in financial markets. Hob=
art is incredibly prolific, and abides by one of my favorite maxims ( https=
://www.thediff.co/manifesto/ ) : assume that people are smart and leverage =
that to figure out what you don=E2=80=99t know about the decisions they mak=
e.

Hobart, in partnership with Tobias Huber, has also written a new book that =
was released this week by Stripe Press: Boom: Bubbles and the End of Stagna=
tion ( https://www.stripe.press/boom ). From the description:

From the Moon landing to the dawning of the atomic age, the decades prior t=
o the 1970s were characterized by the routine invention of transformative t=
echnologies at breakneck speed. By comparison, ours is an age of stagnation=
; of slowing median wage growth, rising inequality, and decelerated scienti=
fic discovery. In Boom, Byrne Hobart and Tobias Huber take an inductive app=
roach to this problem. They track some of the most significant breakthrough=
s of the past 100 years =E2=80=94 from the Manhattan Project and the Apollo=
 program to Moore=E2=80=99s law and Bitcoin =E2=80=94 and reverse-engineer =
how transformative progress arises from the same dynamics that govern finan=
cial bubbles, bringing together small groups with a unified vision, vast fu=
nding, and surprisingly poor accountability. Bubbles, they conclude, aren=
=E2=80=99t all bad=E2=80=94in fact, they create the ideal conditions for tr=
ansformative innovation. Integrating insights from economics, philosophy, a=
nd history, Boom provides a blueprint for accelerating innovation and a pat=
h to unleash a new era of global prosperity.

In this Interview we cover Hobart=E2=80=99s background and path to the news=
letter business, and then dive into the book, which, as I note in the inter=
view, is much more of an exhortation to a better future than a technocratic=
 breakdown of the past. We discuss how he defines a bubble, break down some=
 of the examples in his book, and examine how talent has flowed to differen=
t sectors over time. We also have an extended discussion about globalizatio=
n and China, whether or not AI is in a bubble, and the ongoing vibe shift.

As a reminder, all Stratechery content, including interviews, is available =
as a podcast; click the link at the top of this email to add Stratechery to=
 your podcast player.

