Background

*Byrne Hobart, welcome to Stratechery.*

*BH:* Great to be here.

*Well, you are of course the author of The Diff ( https://www.thediff.co/ )=
. We will get to that in a moment, but the reason to have you on this week =
is you just published a new book with Stripe Press called Boom: Bubbles and=
 the End of Stagnation ( https://www.stripe.press/boom ). First off, congra=
tulations.*

*BH:* Thank you. Yeah, it=E2=80=99s been a journey. My co-author ( https://=
x.com/tobiasahuber ) and I have been working on this one for a really long =
time, and it=E2=80=99s amazing to actually see people holding physical copi=
es of a book that we wrote. And actually hearing people tell me that they r=
ead the book and liked it or, occasionally, read the book and didn=E2=80=99=
t like it that much, but they thought it was cool that I wrote it, so that=
=E2=80=99s good too.

*I have read the book, I have a PDF, I do not have the physical copy, but I=
 did like it, we=E2=80=99re going to spend most of our time talking about t=
he book and its themes, which everyone should go buy, we=E2=80=99ll have a =
link here ( https://www.stripe.press/boom ) or in the show notes. But first=
, as per tradition on these interviews, I want to learn more about you. Tak=
e me back to the beginning, where did you grow up? How did you end up in th=
e newsletter business, writing a book? I want the Byrne Hobart story.*

*BH:* Yeah, so people occasionally ask me for career advice and I have to w=
arn them that this was not the plan and this was not planned, or if it was =
planned, it was not planned well. So let=E2=80=99s see, how far back did we=
 go?

*Where did you grow up? Where were you born?*

*BH:* Born in St. Louis, lived there for a while, lived in El Paso, Texas f=
or a while. I was kind of an indifferent student, got really, really into t=
he stock market in middle school and high school, and spent a lot more time=
 on that than on homework and boring things like that. So when it was time =
to go to college, I realized that I actually did not have the GPA to qualif=
y for really, really good schools, but I did have the standardized test sco=
res to get full rides at other schools, so I did that for a year.

*Many examples of this sort of path.*

*BH:* So I ended up going to a state school on a full ride for a year, and =
I was starting to realize that it=E2=80=99s just not a great use of my time=
.

*=E2=80=9CI want to be on the stock market!=E2=80=9D*

*BH:* So I dropped out and moved to New York and eventually found a kind of=
 random office job actually at a recruiting agency, which was not a really =
good job for me because I=E2=80=99m not an extrovert and I don=E2=80=99t li=
ke hassling people and sending lots of cold emails and doing cold calls and=
 things like that. So fortunately, I didn=E2=80=99t really have to make a d=
ecision there because the recruiting firm =E2=80=94 it was actually kind of=
 cool because they were doing quant and financial software engineering recr=
uiting, so got to talk to a lot of really interesting people, but at the ti=
me, half the firm=E2=80=99s business was Lehman Brothers, and then half of =
the rest was Merrill Lynch. So in the summer of 2008, the business just com=
pletely vaporized, and so I had to find something else to do.

*(laughing) Can=E2=80=99t imagine why, talk about a dependency risk.*

*BH:* Yeah. So yeah, I learned a bit about what quants do and how they thin=
k and talk, and I learned a lot about customer concentration.

*Yes, that=E2=80=99s the phrase I was looking for exactly.*

*BH:* From there I ended up getting a freelance job and a marketing agency =
that turned into a full-time job at that agency, and then I kind of was in =
the marketing world for a while doing SEO and social media stuff, generally=
 in the white hat to gray hat range, but it was an interesting space and ca=
used me to think a lot about search and learn a lot about search. So I kind=
 of ended up combining those two interests and I started writing these blog=
 posts that were basically my view as an online marketer of how some of the=
 then prominent Internet companies work. So pieces on things like, =E2=80=
=9CHere are all the tricks that Yelp uses to rank well for the names of bus=
inesses=E2=80=9D, and, =E2=80=9CHere are all the pieces of evidence we have=
 that LinkedIn and Facebook are doing this brutal battle to rank first for =
people=E2=80=99s full names=E2=80=9D.

Through writing that blog, I up getting on the radar of a hedge fund, and w=
hat I was told after I got hired, was that there was a portfolio manager at=
 this hedge fund, SAC Capital, he emailed a ton of people asking them he ne=
eded a new analyst, he was asking them for recommendations, and he said it =
was really weird that two different people he knew recommended the same col=
lege dropout with no financial experience, and that was me. I think if one =
person had done it would=E2=80=99ve been kind of easy to ignore, but if two=
 different people recommend the same guy, then you at least want to talk to=
 them.

So I talked to them and I think that was my first experience of just being =
in a room with exceptionally smart people and being kind of the slow one an=
d I realized this when I was explaining something about how Google rankings=
 worked, and I could just see them get it and instantly get bored and insta=
ntly want me to move on the next thing.

*And you=E2=80=99ve been trying to walk people over this line all this time=
, I know what you mean.*

*BH:* Yeah.

*I know that exact experience you=E2=80=99re talking about and I think beca=
use I have a pretty similar =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s completely different tha=
n yours, but I was an English teacher and the Internet, it=E2=80=99s kind o=
f like the standardized test point, it=E2=80=99s a sort of a pure meritocra=
cy when you=E2=80=99re running analysis online and you=E2=80=99re either go=
ing to get picked up or you=E2=80=99re not and then you get invited into th=
ese rooms and into these meetings and you=E2=80=99re like, =E2=80=9CWhoa, I=
 wasn=E2=80=99t familiar with that=E2=80=9D, I did not go to Harvard, to yo=
ur point.*

*BH:* Yeah, so that was really fun. I worked there for a couple years, ende=
d up getting laid off, and then I did a brief detour into the crypto world.=
 I worked at 21.co, Balaji Srinivasan=E2=80=99s thing ( https://x.com/balaj=
is ) , which was also really fun, was actually a room with smarter people, =
which was a really weird disconcerting experience after I was sort of getti=
ng used to the idea that, =E2=80=9COkay, if you get into the hedge fund ind=
ustry, you get to talk to people who their brains are a little bit over-clo=
cked, maybe it=E2=80=99s the Adderall, but they=E2=80=99re also just really=
 smart=E2=80=9D and then going to a tech company that is hardcore crypto pe=
ople and chip designers and people like that in 2015, yeah, it was more of =
that.

So did that for a while, and then my wife and I decided we really ought to =
=E2=80=94 we were going to have our first kid and we would sometimes walk a=
round in San Francisco and walk past the needles, and my wife would talk ab=
out how she=E2=80=99s thinking about steering her stroller around the needl=
es and things and this is just not a great place to have a kid or have a fa=
mily unless you=E2=80=99re really, really rich, and since that was not the =
case, we decided to move to New York. New York is a weirdly great city to b=
e either really rich or really broke, and it=E2=80=99s actually reasonable =
in a lot of spaces in between. You do have public transportation, a lot of =
things to do, a lot of people and people visit all the time, so it=E2=80=99=
s good to have central locations like that.

I went back into the finance world doing basically data-driven equity resea=
rch, this is some of what I had done on the hedge fund side was finding int=
eresting data sets that we can use to predict company fundamentals, build m=
odels of fundamentals based on those data sets, and then at the fund it was=
 use that to predict what the stock will do. Then for the data providers, i=
t was sell research reports and data feeds to funds, and then they will pre=
dict what the stock will do. That was pretty fun actually. So that=E2=80=99=
s based on alternative data, it is a really good way to understand pretty m=
uch the gap between what do the accounting financials say and what are the =
true underlying economics of the business because over the long, long run, =
they have to tie out, your cumulative cash flows do have to sum to your cum=
ulative net profits over a sufficiently long period, or you got your accoun=
ting numbers wrong. But over the short term, the accounting numbers are not=
 necessarily a great guide to how the business works.

*Well, I mean, that=E2=80=99s all very interesting, and you have this Steve=
 Jobs-esque look backwards and you can see connecting the dots, but how=E2=
=80=99d you start writing a newsletter? Were you doing this simultaneously =
then, or did you just start then?*

*BH:* Yeah, I was doing Medium posts here and there ( https://byrnehobart.m=
edium.com/ ) when I had just random ideas that I felt like writing down, or=
 I went to a handful of little conferences and I just had a really good tim=
e and people seemed really interested in some of the ideas I was kicking ar=
ound. I was like, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve delivered this same spiel on this s=
ame topic to five different people, I should just write it down and tell pe=
ople, =E2=80=98I=E2=80=99ve written a thing on this, you should read it=E2=
=80=99.=E2=80=9D

So I was doing a little of that, and it started to do reasonably well. I ha=
d a couple of Medium pieces on things like California and housing ( https:/=
/byrnehobart.medium.com/peak-california-7cf97baecaf0 ) and I was looking ba=
ck at the stories of early Airbnb and thinking about how if real estate had=
 been as expensive then as it was at the time that I was writing in 2018, 2=
019 =E2=80=94 Airbnb, they probably just would=E2=80=99ve run out of money =
and they probably would=E2=80=99ve been designers at Facebook or something,=
 but they would not have actually been able to build Airbnb, it was a very =
close thing.

So I=E2=80=99ve written a couple of these pieces, and then I was thinking a=
bout my career progression, and it felt like there was a lot that was fun a=
bout the job, but also there=E2=80=99s a lot more money in predicting the n=
ext quarter, and there=E2=80=99s just a lot less demand for deep research i=
nto long-term company fundamentals and just a lot less demand for thinking =
about their economic models and understanding them, except in the sense tha=
t it=E2=80=99s instrumentally useful in that it makes it a little bit easie=
r to predict the next quarter.

So yeah, I decided I should find something else to do and take a break. I r=
eally started the newsletter as just a way to keep busy during the break in=
 a way to make sure that people didn=E2=80=99t forget that I existed, becau=
se I know this happens sometimes where you=E2=80=99re in an industry for a =
while and everyone knows you, you=E2=80=99ve got lots of friends, people ar=
e always asking you to hang out, and then if you=E2=80=99re not actively wo=
rking, people just have fewer reminders of your existence, they don=E2=80=
=99t necessarily reach out. And after a while, people kind of vaguely remem=
ber who you were, but you=E2=80=99re not really there anymore. So I wanted =
to avoid that, and I figured newsletters are just a good way to have my nam=
e in people=E2=80=99s inbox every couple days, that was originally my plan.=
 It was Monday, Wednesday, Friday.

So that takes us to late 2019, early 2020, I had actually a very extended i=
nterview process with a hedge fund that I really wanted to work for and got=
 to the very end of the process, and they said it was a close decision, but=
 no, but I had done some research as part of that interview process, and I =
thought that was fun too. That was fun to write this stuff up and kind of b=
uild a mental model of something I hadn=E2=80=99t really worked on before a=
nd so I decided I=E2=80=99m just going to keep doing that, I=E2=80=99m goin=
g to sort of larp as having the job that I=E2=80=99d like to have, which is=
 just spend a lot of time reading, talk to interesting people and write up =
thoughts periodically on what=E2=80=99s going on in the world.

So I was doing the newsletter and then in yeah, January and February of 202=
0 started seeing more and more alarming headlines out of China and then out=
 of other places about this novel respiratory infection and I was thinking,=
 =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m probably not going to be going on very many job inter=
views in March and April of 2020, but people don=E2=80=99t seem all that wo=
rried, so why don=E2=80=99t I just turn this into a paid product? I bet peo=
ple will buy annual subscriptions, they=E2=80=99ll completely regret this w=
hen the economy collapses and they=E2=80=99re looking for every last dollar=
, but at least they=E2=80=99ll have a little bit of money and something to =
do as the world falls apart=E2=80=9D. So yeah, I turned on paid subscriptio=
ns in February of 2020, and then the COVID era was just a really, really go=
od era, as I=E2=80=99m sure you recall.

Early COVID was amazing for newsletter writers. I think part of what happen=
ed was people, they anchored their workday to when they leave for work, and=
 if leaving for work just means you open your laptop and you=E2=80=99re at =
work now, they actually have this extra chunk of time, and it=E2=80=99s a g=
ood place to do things that are kind of work-like, but not strictly work, a=
nd reading a newsletter is one of those things. And in fact, I was looking =
back, I think I subscribed to Stratechery for the first time, and I believe=
 April of 2020. I had been reading the free issues for a long time, but yea=
h, I became a paid subscriber just then.

*You needed something to do every day. Well, I mean, this is actually a poi=
nt, you gave me one of my all-time favorite compliments a few years ago whe=
n you said something to the effect of =E2=80=9C10 PM to 6 AM=E2=80=A6=E2=80=
=9D, which is daytime for me in Taiwan, =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6was the Ben Thomp=
son kill zone=E2=80=9D, and that I might come out with sort of a take overn=
ight that invalidated what you are going to publish the next day, I absolut=
ely love it, but truth be told, I find you very intimidating. You published=
, it still seems to be five days a week, a schedule that I abandoned years =
ago, and you wrote a book. I mean, in my defense, I do, do four podcasts a =
week as well, but to steal a line from Tyler Cowen ( https://x.com/tylercow=
en ) , what is your executive function? What happened to Monday, Wednesday,=
 Friday? Where did this productivity come from?*

*BH:* Yeah, so what actually happened there was the week before I turned on=
 paid subscriptions, I decided I=E2=80=99m going to do a campaign, I=E2=80=
=99m going to seriously pitch this over and over, and every day I=E2=80=99m=
 going to publish a newsletter and every day I=E2=80=99m going to give peop=
le a new reason to subscribe. So from one of them, it was like, =E2=80=9CHe=
re=E2=80=99s what I=E2=80=99ve written so far, here=E2=80=99s what people h=
ave said=E2=80=9D, and then for one of them, it=E2=80=99s like, =E2=80=9CHe=
re=E2=80=99s what I think about the economics of paid newsletters=E2=80=9D,=
 and I hit this point on cancellation, which I was kind of proud of, which =
